# TypeScript Code Smells (from PR review)

## 1. Don't call a pure function twice for the same value

If you need both the result and a derived check (empty, length), compute once into a local.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — .trim() runs twice
if (value == null || value.trim().length === 0) return null;
return value.trim();

// ✅ GOOD
const result = (value ?? "").trim();
return result.length === 0 ? null : result;
```

Same idea for `.toLowerCase()`, `.map()`, expensive lookups, etc.

## 2. Trust validated DTO types — don't re-check `typeof`

When a value comes from a class-validator / Nest DTO that already constrains the type (e.g. `@IsString()`), type the helper as that DTO type instead of `unknown` + runtime `typeof` throws.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — DTO already guarantees string; redundant runtime check
const validateFoo = (value: unknown): string | null => {
  if (typeof value !== "string") {
    throw new BadRequestException("foo must be a string");
  }
  // ...
};

// ✅ GOOD — trust the validated pipe; keep domain checks (enum, empty → null)
const validateFoo = (value: string): string | null => {
  const trimmed = value.trim();
  if (trimmed.length === 0) return null;
  // domain validation only...
};
```

**When `unknown` / `typeof` is still OK:** untrusted inputs (GeoJSON properties, raw query params without a DTO, JSON columns, external APIs).

## Checklist before PR

- [ ] No repeated `.trim()` / map / lookup for the same expression
- [ ] Helpers accepting DTO fields use DTO types, not defensive `typeof` that duplicates pipes
